data.name: Acceptance
data.description: Explore ways to work with and support people who think, act and work differently than you.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Become a student of others, especially those who think differently than you.
Put yourself in the other person's shoes. Ask yourself how they might perceive or make sense of a situation.
Aim to understand first without passing judgment; ask questions to explore the other person's perspective in greater detail before sharing your own view or explaining why an idea won't work.
Think through past situations where you were less accepting than you could have been. Identify 3-4 things you could have done differently and incorporate those approaches in the future.

data.name: Accountability
data.description: Be aware of how personal responsibility contributes to your success. Learn how to take ownership by addressing problems and admitting shortcomings.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Take accountability when something goes wrong; acknowledge your mistakes and how you will address them.
Communicate your responsibilities in a proactive manner.
Ask your manager or colleagues for instances in which you could have taken more accountability; make changes with what you learn.
When something goes wrong, don't blame others; focus instead on how the issue can be fixed quickly. Play a leadership role in driving resolution.

data.name: Active Listening
data.description: Master the art of listening and asking questions to elicit more information, understand people more deeply and grasp the unspoken.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Make it a point to fully understand before being understood. Ask what, how, when and why to gain a deeper understanding of what's being communicated to you.
Balance the amount of time you spend speaking and listening. Let the other person do more than 50% of the talking.
Hold off on sharing your ideas until you fully explore theirs; work through their ideas before moving on to your own.
Verify that you're on the same page by summarizing or paraphrasing what's been said.
Use body language to convey that you're listening; make eye contact and lean slightly forward.

data.name: Appreciation & Recognition
data.description: Grasp a full understanding of people to better show recognition of and gratitude for the work of others.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Write down a list of 3-5 things that you value in the person.
Start using the phrase "I appreciate...".
Practice saying thank you several times a day.
Ensure that you're recognizing even the smallest efforts and affirming others for their contributions.

data.name: Assertiveness
data.description: Find ways to build confidence and self-assurance without becoming overconfident or too forceful.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Speak up 10% more frequently or directly than what comes naturally to you.
Think about topics you care about; communicate more frequently and directly on these issues.
Present ideas without sounding positional; be willing to modify your approach to gain support from others.
Identify people who are more assertive than you are and mimic their styles; think about how they present their ideas and what you can learn from them.
Practice what you want to say to instill confidence and precision in your approach. Avoid using words and phrases that undermine your credibility.

data.name: Attention to Detail
data.description: Develop habits to achieve thoroughness and accuracy without losing sight of the big picture.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Accept the fact that details may not be your forte and that you would benefit from receiving help.
Solicit help from a detail-oriented colleague to consider what you might be overlooking; learn from how that person processes information and what they do with it.
Identify areas where you need to pay especially close attention to detail; focus and make a plan so that you're more deliberate.
When you need to pay close attention to details, ensure your mindset and surroundings are amenable to focusing on your work.

data.name: Awareness of Others' Needs
data.description: Cultivate interpersonal awareness and develop greater sensitivity to the needs and interests of others.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Become a student of others; identify and incorporate 2-3 things you learn into the way you work.
Always assume that your perception of others is incomplete; see how their styles compare to yours, and adapt your behavior to work together more effectively.
Observe the person's actions closely to build a deeper understanding of who they are; keep in mind that there is more than meets the eye.
Consider how your communication style comes across to others; if the way you speak or convey ideas can come across as insensitive, learn to soften your language and approach to be more sensitive.
Use a cautious approach when communicating with others that you're comfortable with.

data.name: Building Stability
data.description: Cultivate practices that create a consistent and predictable environment to enable your own and others' productivity.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Begin with the end in mind; envision yourself in the most advantageous position.
Identify obstacles that you believe limit your success; systematically work to minimize their impact.
Define what stability means to you and how you can create it for yourself and your colleagues.
Explore with a coworker what you both believe would be the most stable situation; figure out a plan to get there.

data.name: Coach & Develop
data.description: Engage in the learning and development process for junior members both through formal programs and informal opportunities.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Invest time with those who need your support; most leaders don't spend enough time helping people learn and grow. Make this a principle aspect of how you lead.
Consider those managers or people who have helped you grow the most. Think about how they helped you develop and what made them effective as a coach.
Make sure each of your employees has a robust development plan that helps them grow their skills for the current role and beyond.

Ask your staff what areas they could use help or support with; some people are hesitant to ask for help and you may need to ask more than once to ensure they are comfortable sharing where they could use help to improve.

Coach a person or team outside of work in an activity or sport that you have significant experience with; reflect on what worked or didn't work in your coaching style and how you can apply learnings in the workplace.

data.name: Collaboration
data.description: Discover ways to create an environment where individuals feel comfortable expressing their ideas through an open and meaningful exchange of perspectives.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Realize that true collaboration requires trust and a personal commitment to working together.
Solicit others' ideas before sharing your own; build on them first instead of countering them.
Ask for opinions and suggestions; include them in conversation and solutions.
Encourage others to facilitate dialogue, particularly when you have a stake in the outcome.

data.name: Compassion
data.description: Establish a sense of regard for the emotions and feelings of others.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Take time to anticipate how others will react to your ideas before sharing them.
Remind yourself that considering the thoughts and feelings of others doesn't necessarily mean that you agree.
Guard against countering what others think and feel; this sets the stage for defensive competition in the relationship.
Intentionally look for areas of agreement to build on instead of finding areas of disagreement.

data.name: Compromise
data.description: Develop the ability to build consensus through a willingness to concede points, make tradeoffs and secure support through mutually beneficial solutions.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Allow for options that may be acceptable, even if they are not ideal.
Rank issues by importance before negotiating with others.
Consider alternative agreements that will benefit both parties; create a foundational agreement and build from there.
Have discussions with others to understand what matters to them; focus on finding common ground.
Start by building a stronger relationship to further your ability to understand the needs of others and facilitate more opportunities for compromise.

data.name: Critical Thinking
data.description: Seek the capability to analyze issues in depth, understand implications and weigh tradeoffs of alternative strategies.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Research and fact-check a wide range of information before forming conclusions.
Engage others to test your thinking, and ask for their perspectives.
Explore alternative options even when they are not readily apparent; brainstorm the possibilities and take creative angles to fully examine options and their implications.
Don't conduct all your analysis in one sitting; break up critical thinking activities so that you can approach them with a fresh set of eyes.
Repeatedly ask yourself what you are missing. Second guess and check your analysis, approaches and solutions to address possible opportunities.

data.name: Cross Cultural Awareness
data.description: Become a global student, learning various cultural habits, norms, expectations and world views along with their implications.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Pick one country/culture you would like to learn about. Study its geography, culture, dress and cuisine then speak to people from that country and learn from their predominant language.
Watch the news on an international channel, or pay particular attention to the news from outside your home country. Read international books or magazines to understand current trends and interests.
Try the food and drinks of cultures you are interested in, preferably by traveling to that country. Pay careful attention to the etiquette and social interactions that distinguish the food culture.
Seek out a work colleague from a country of interest and have that person share tips on how best to work with people in their culture.
Learn about the customs and traditions from a culture of interest. Seek to adapt to others instead of assuming they'll adapt to your customs and traditions.

data.name: Culture
data.description: Learn how the beliefs, behaviors and practices of an organization determine how work is completed, what is valued, how people are evaluated and rewarded, and how perceptions affect organizational effectiveness.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Assemble a team of people to define ways to improve the culture of your team; review their results and implement the most viable strategies.
Collaborate on creating a strong workplace culture and leverage applicable ideas to effect culture and drive change within your team.
Identify and interview a leader you know who has built a strong, healthy workplace culture. Solicit and test ideas for how you can improve your team's culture.

Make the creation of a productive workplace culture one of your key goals for the next year. Spend a portion of your time on activities like teambuilding, recognizing accomplishments, and helping others understand business goals and the culture you are trying to create.
Open up cultural conversations by speaking with others about what their core values are and how they relate to the surrounding environment.

data.name: Customer Focus
data.description: Refine the communications and service skills necessary to create positive relationships with potential and existing customers.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Use your daily personal interactions to observe the quality of customer service at various businesses. Consider what made each interaction a positive or negative experience, and utilize the practices of businesses that offer the best experience.
Listen to your peers speak to customers and learn what strategies seem to work best.
Study customer service data or metrics your company has on hand. These are the best source of perspectives about how you are doing, and can be highly instructive on how to improve your skills.

After you engage with a customer, evaluate yourself on a 1-10 scale on how well you did. Compare your evaluation with any available customer feedback. Consider how to modify your approach to raise your self-evaluation going forward.
Research a company known for outstanding customer service. Read several articles or a book about how they treat customers to learn tips that you can use.
Become a great listener by cultivating empathy. Listen to understand what they really need fixed to be happy. Ask lots of penetrating questions to get to the root of their troubles.

data.name: Decision Making
data.description: Build a capacity to discern good decisions from bad ones and strengthen the ability to make better, faster decisions.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Reflect on five recent decisions and consider whether your decision-making pace was too fast or slow.
Use the 80/20 rule as most decisions can be made without complete information; aim for good decisions instead of perfect decisions.
Begin with the end in mind and map your decisions backward to anticipate potential pitfalls and successes.
Identify and utilize one of the widely available decision-making frameworks that can help you make decisions with speed and efficiency
Identify and utilize a network of stakeholders who will provide feedback within your decision making activities.

data.name: Delegation
data.description: Entrust tasks to others and provide instruction to help them reach objectives and goals.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Make a list of activities that can be easily delegated. With varying levels of instruction, consider who could perform each activity.
Don't expect others to perform as well as you do when you first hand over a task; show appreciation when others do things well and help them focus on attainable improvements.
Decide how much time you would like to free up through delegation. Use that as a benchmark, then adjust your workload depending on your successes.
Reflect on why it might be difficult for you to delegate, and work to overcome the barriers that are holding you back.
Periodically measure the success of your delegation by checking the improvements in pacing and success of your team members.

data.name: Digital Communication
data.description: Leverage technology to deliver engaging virtual presentations and communications.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Separate content from process; let someone else deal with the technology while you deal with the content.
Avoid using a wall of words or presentation visuals that look like scripts.
Keep it simple; use visual models or images to convey complex ideas.
Build in interaction and real-time dialogue or activities to invite participation.
Ask questions that are focused and well articulated.

data.name: Drive Action
data.description: Develop the capacity to move from theory to application and drive progress on work efforts.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Identify your objectives and write down three to five steps for each that are essential to succeed.
Ask a detail-oriented colleague what important steps you might be missing.
Lower your standards if they are too high in certain areas; sometimes good enough is good enough. Move past the details in order to make something happen.
Rate the risks of not getting something done and who will be affected by it.
Encourage others to help you by articulating a plan and requesting their advocacy.

data.name: Embracing Change
data.description: Tackle changes head-on by letting go of routine and accepting new circumstances as possibilities.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Choose to accept the reality that nothing in life stays the same and everything will change over time; expect and plan for change.
Be flexible and consider creative possibilities; utilize change in the environment as a way to foster progress toward goals.
Speak to others about how you can embrace change together and the opportunities it offers.
If you are anxious or concerned about upcoming changes, avoid thinking about them for 24-48 hours to release the anxiety. Come back to them when your reaction to change is less emotionally charged.
Make incremental steps towards supporting change over a long period of time.

data.name: Encouraging Innovation
data.description: Embolden yourself and others to think big and explore new possibilities.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Spend time with imaginative people who easily see new possibilities; they can be contagious.
Identify dreams that you tend to brush aside; find opportunities to take steps to realizing those dreams.
Pick one innovative idea and be willing to take reasonable risks to put it into motion.
Don't be the hero; collaboration is the birthplace of innovation.

data.name: Engagement
data.description: Develop rational and emotional commitment to the organization's mission and values. Catalyze your own purpose with these to push for higher productivity and performance.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Use the SurePeople engagement survey in the Pulse to understand how engaged your staff members are currently.
Career development is a primary engagement driver. Ask team members what their career goals are, then match new assignments and your coaching to help them develop toward their career goals.
Research employee engagement and discuss with others how to enhance engagement. Apply the lessons lear strategies that best fit your team and situation.
Connect your team's work to the larger company purpose and emphasize how the team's contributions are helping to fulfill company goals.

Think about what motivates and inspires you to do your best work, then ask your staff the same question. It is likely they may be inspired by different things than you are, so work to inspire them on their terms, not your own.
Practice vigilance with disjointed teams that are spread out across geographies. Learn to build the team morale by employing strategies to foster involvement and belonging.

data.name: Engaging Conversation
data.description: Sharpen your skills at initiating conversation, getting people to open up to you and connecting more deeply.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Write a list of your favorite 10 open-ended questions and use them in conversations.
Identify 3-4 phrases that draw more information from others, such as, "I'm glad you said that. Can you expand on that?"  Or, "Tell me more about that."
Strive to listen in order to learn and understand, not to agree or disagree.
Observe good conversationalists to see how they initiate interactions; look for things they do that you can emulate.
Learn what is important to others, then incorporate those subjects into your conversations. Sometimes this involves asking about the person's life outside the office.

data.name: Execution Capability
data.description: Drive the execution of tasks and realization of objectives by actively facilitating results and managing processes.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Evaluate your group's effectiveness at implementing initiatives, including the quality and speed of their solutions. Examine the last 2-3 big initiatives they implemented and highlight learnings that will help the group improve for the future.
Read a few case studies of companies who are highly responsive to customers. Distill learnings and apply them within your team.

Include an after action review or project post-mortem for all significant projects. Include all team members who worked on the project and harvest what the team sees as learnings that can be applied to future efforts.
Talk with your team about the importance of translating ideas into solutions that can be deployed rapidly. Emphasize the importance of speed in getting things accomplished.
Create a team that goes out to other groups, inside or outside your company, to learn how they approach project execution and what can be learned from different approaches.

data.name: Financial & Business Acumen
data.description: Continually sharpen the ability to assess fiscal scenarios and make well-informed decisions.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Become comfortable with reading financial reports to understand terminology and better recognize patterns that will help inform better decision making.
Ask a friend or colleague with financial knowledge to walk you through the basics of common financial and accounting practices.
Read your company's annual report, and those of a few competitor companies, to better understand your specific industry's financial patterns and practices.
Participate in your team's budgeting and financial management processes to get involved in regular conversation and strategy.
Consider joining the board of a non-profit organization and participate in the budget or finance committee to gain exposure to the practice.

data.name: Flexibility
data.description: Build your personal adaptability and become more flexible in your work and relationships.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Start being flexible in incremental steps and recognize your progress; look for new ways to complete tasks you've mastered.
Say yes to opportunities you'd normally turn down; grow comfortable with being more adaptable in your approach.
When an uncomfortable situation arises, ask yourself if there's really a substantive reason not to be flexible.
Honestly assess areas in which you may not be flexible; consider why that is and how you can improve over time.

data.name: Focus
data.description: Maintain your focus to concentrate on tasks, campaigns and objectives.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Think of your mind as a guided missile; identify your targets and stay locked on to them by intentionally ignoring distractions.
Practice completing one task before starting another.
Consider the possibility that a lack of focus may be related to your time management, lifestyle or habits; change whatever is holding you back.
Focus on working in time-limited bursts; research has shown that working for 90-minute periods followed by a short break can maximize productivity.

data.name: Forethought & Planning
data.description: Learn to think before you act, develop a more robust thought process and use a methodical approach to organizing and executing work.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Stop before you start. Begin with a picture of the end in mind and then determine how to reach that point.
Write down the series of steps needed to achieve the goal. Ask yourself what might be the smaller steps between the big steps.
Build your planning skills by working on a project alongside someone who is known to be a proficient planner. Observe the steps he/she takes to create detailed plans.
Engage others to help you refine your ultimate goal and the plans you make to get there.

data.name: Getting to the Point
data.description: Enhance the ability to use concise communication that conveys your thinking in a succinct, powerful manner.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Identify and hone your message to make it as succinct and powerful as possible; write it down and revise it until it is concise and clear.
Think of how you could condense what you say into a brief elevator pitch.
Share your answer or conclusion first, then go back to fill in details as needed.
Be careful not to use qualifying or extraneous words that will dilute your message and the impact of your delivery.
Time how long it takes you to deliver your message; work toward shortening the length without losing your main point.

data.name: Giving & Receiving Feedback
data.description: Learn how to better give and receive feedback for the sake of improving performance.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Ask yourself how you can best convey your desire to help and support others.
Share criticism in a way that you would want to receive it; put yourself in their shoes as you communicate.
Avoid simply pointing out what you don't like; share what you do like about what the person is doing, then suggest alternatives or areas of improvement.
Identify and explain several ways you think your critique is beneficial.

data.name: Incorporating Creativity
data.description: Develop yourself as an imaginative thinker capable of generating novel ideas and strategies.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Encourage brainstorming sessions where there are no bad ideas, and suspend evaluation until later.
Designate a certain amount of time to outside-of-the-box thinking, both individually and as a group.
Intentionally pair creative people with those who are not as creative, then invite them to do some imaginative brainstorming.
When trying to generate creative solutions, get out of your day-to-day environment to encourage new thinking.
Determine when creativity comes most naturally to you. Analyze the conditions that help you obtain a creative mindset and focus your efforts on recreating that environment.

data.name: Inspiring Trust
data.description: Learn to earn the trust of others through authenticity, humility, respect and credibility.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Treat others fairly and respectfully to create a safe working environment where others feel comfortable to be themselves.
Strive to be honest and transparent while consistently working to open lines of communication.
Uphold a dependable track record of delivering on commitments. Be reliable by always doing what you've agreed to and learn when to say no to commitments to stay accountable.
Be a role model for others by holding yourself to high levels of integrity and inspiring others to follow your lead.
Trust others to have good intentions. Give people the benefit of the doubt that they're trying to do the right thing even though they're methods may be different than yours.

data.name: Leadership
data.description: Learn to Influence others through communication and action. Enlist practices to engage them to follow your direction and motivate them to perform to their highest potential.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Review your PRISM Portrait and spend time considering how to leverage your natural leadership style to maximum effect. Self-knowledge is so important when we hold this role, because without self-awareness we can't be thoughtful and strategic about how we operate with others.
Define what you want to be known for as a leader; consider how well you are doing in each of these areas and take steps to address the weaker areas.
Work to your strengths and find people who complement you. Address your weaknesses and turn to others to support your natural shortcomings.
Use the SurePeople Leadership survey to understand perceptions of your leadership among your team.
Read biographies of leaders who inspire you and apply learnings to how you operate as a leader.
Utilize a mentor or coach to help you hone your leadership approach and address current shortcomings.

Remember the Smarter Faster Better paradox. Understand you don't need to be the smartest person in the room and learn to leverage others. Slow down and optimize your thinking and decision making to pace yourself. Be better with others versus better than.

data.name: Leading Change
data.description: Challenge the status quo and initiate the creation of innovative practices and culture-setting. Learn to lead others through these changes and understand how to handle difficulties along the way.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Clearly define the changes you desire, the obstacles to be faced, the payoff of making the changes, and the behaviors or practices you want others to modify.
Invest time in communicating and discussing the changes you are seeking with others. In most cases, this requires multiple discussions to get people on board with the changes you are seeking.

Be willing to take calculated personal risk to achieve your goals. This may involve doing things you haven't tried before, pushing others to shift or change their views, or committing to goals that will stretch your capabilities.

Change agents are quick to try new ideas. Evaluate your willingness and speed to embrace change and what is holding you back from moving faster. Seek to limit or overcome the things that are holding you back.

Seek out advocates and ambassadors for change. Leverage them heavily and creatively to create a groundswell for change. Getting skeptics to see there's a vocal group in support of change may help break down their resistance.

data.name: Logic & Rationale
data.description: Use facts, information and analysis to determine an effective course of action.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Think in terms of both pros and cons; work to establish a positive and negative case to fully evaluate any decision.
Ask yourself what the most practical course of action is; consider how others might approach the same problem.
Determine the worst thing that can happen and whether you're capable of dealing with the risks.
Outline the primary data points that support your opinion, then look for missing data or weaknesses in your logic. Address them by finding more data that completes your rationale.
Recognize your thinking style and learn how to adapt accordingly.

data.name: Managing Conflict
data.description: Implement and revisit best practices and strategies for managing interpersonal conflicts. Focus on each individuals experience and tendencies to help them move through adversity.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Reflect on how you can effectively manage your emotions during disagreements or conflict; devise a strategy for how to keep yourself and others calm in difficult circumstances. This can include removing yourself from the situation or postponing the discussion until you and others can address it in a non-emotional manner.

Look for underlying emotional needs. Do they need to win? To save face? How can you meet the underlying need and still get what you want? Use the SurePeople relationship advisor to see how they think, and look at your own conflict style as well as theirs.

If you are mediating conflict, talk to parties on both sides of a conflict separately to understand what's most important to them. Use what you learn to build consensus on meeting the crucial needs of both parties, even if they have to acquiesce on some of their less critical points.

Summarize the disagreement for someone who is not involved and get their recommendation on how you might resolve the matter. Sometimes a person outside of the workplace can help you think through the issue in a new way.

Think proactively about mutually beneficial solutions. Find a win for the organization and diffuse the idea that one party wins and the other loses. Ensure that both parties feel advocated for in order to drive them to support the greater organizational need.

Start addressing the conflict by highlighting the points of agreement between the parties. Use this as a basis to build trust and make progress, then build on it by working to craft mutually beneficial solutions.

data.name: Managing Differences
data.description: Address conflict before it happens by celebrating individuality and building better relationships.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Choose to view differences as challenges to overcome and not as barriers.
Channel the mindset of an objective observer; investigate viewpoints instead of passing judgment on them.
Explore the perspectives of others with a belief that they always know something you do not.
Express your desire to close the gap on personal differences; addressing differences with authenticity and humility can lead to a breakthrough.
Use the relationship advisor to identify strategies for working more effectively with others.

data.name: Managing Emotions
data.description: Determine ways to maintain objectivity and manage emotions during trying circumstances.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Focus on the facts in a situation; stay calm and follow up at a later time when you can maintain objectivity and make meaningful progress.
Try ranking difficult situations by pricing them; ask yourself, Is this a $1000, $100, $10 or $1 issue? Focus on the big issues, not the small ones.
Regulate your emotions like a volume control. Set the minimum and maximum, then determine where you should fall. Work to stay within this range.
Objectively examine how you react in tense situations. Gauge yourself by comparing your reactions to those of people you admire.

data.name: Motivate & Inspire
data.description: Develop techniques to organize people around a goal and guide them towards a shared objective.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Identify the central mission and focus for your team; make sure these primary objectives are captured and discussed frequently in a positive light.
Invite others to help set the goals and brainstorm steps to get there.
Help others clarify their roles in achieving the goals and objectives; ask them to articulate ways they can contribute to what the team is trying to accomplish.
Draw on what you find inspiring to help motivate others to achieve; share compelling examples that will energize colleagues.
Learn what motivates your people. Forget about what motivates you, and find out what motivates them.

data.name: Negotiation
data.description: Develop tact and prowess for creating win-win solutions.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Actively listen to others in order to build trust and strengthen the relationship.
Seek a win-win outcome in order to make agreement more easily obtainable.
Highlight commonalities; focus on middle ground that sets the stage for agreement.
Acknowledge counterpoints and objections by discussing them rather than overriding them.
Expand your thinking to understand that there are possibilities not yet thought of that could make for an even better situation.

data.name: Patience
data.description: Learn to work at different paces, deal with delays and stay calm under pressure.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Choose to not sweat the small stuff; identify a few ways to test and build patience.
Be 10% kinder for 10% longer when others test your patience.
Get in the slowest line and enjoy interacting with others.
When you find yourself getting impatient and agitated, take a small break and leave the room; try to re-enter with a calm, patient attitude.

data.name: Personal Fulfillment
data.description: Overcome the need for perfection, find personal balance and learn to seek gratification from everyday situations and scenarios.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Create a daily journal listing the high points of the day with two or three good things that you appreciated.
Practice identifying two things you are grateful for every day; verbalize them to yourself or others.
Know when to accept a good outcome rather than waiting for a perfect one.
Dial back your standards if they are too high in certain areas; sometimes good enough is good enough.
Perfectionism can hinder your ability to feel a sense of satisfaction. Focus on the incremental successes of projects and initiatives, versus seeing less than perfect achievements as failures.

data.name: Persuasion
data.description: Gain the skills necessary for influencing others to support your requests and ideas.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Think through and write down how others will benefit from doing what you want.
Separate facts from feelings, but use both to rally your audience around your way of thinking.
Read about historical figures who had success in getting conflicting parties to agree; adopt some of their ideas and approaches.
Make it a habit to know what those around you value; position your ideas to reflect their interests.

data.name: Presentation Skills
data.description: Improve information delivery by using tried and true techniques of effective presenters.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Write down the main point you want to get across so that if nothing else, people remember that one thing.
Practice your presentation at least 5-10 times before delivering it; share it with a trusted colleague or friend and get their feedback.
Recognize the fact that you're in control of the information your audience receives and that they're relying on you to be the expert.
Create a memorable and compelling opening to your presentation. A provocative start can quickly create interest.
Follow the old adage "facts tell and stories sell" by developing multiple examples or analogies that can help you get your thoughts across.

data.name: Presenting Facts
data.description: Support your ideas with information, facts and details that help you make your case.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Separate facts from feelings; focus on the facts and not your emotional reactions to a situation.
Write down key facts, figures and points before presenting your case.
Create a diagram or graphic to explain your thought process to others.
Make sure your audience understands how the facts tie in to the main objective.
Keep it simple; a lot of facts are hard to retain, whereas a few can be compelling.
None
None

data.name: Public Speaking
data.description: Improve public speaking skills by using tried and true techniques of effective speakers.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Write down the main point you want to get across so that if nothing else, people remember that one thing.
Practice your speech with a trusted colleague or friend and get their feedback.
Recognize that the fear of public speaking is a common obstacle, and determine what methods have helped you overcome it in the past.
Break up your presentation with open-ended questions along the way to invite engagement.
Be aware of your audience so that you can easily transition from presenting to asking questions or from painting the big picture to diving into details.

data.name: Receptivity to New Ideas
data.description: Become receptive to alternative opinions by understanding different forms of thinking.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Think of yourself as an idea-miner; sort through ideas to find golden nuggets, and polish rough ideas into gems.
Try to see what the other person sees; put yourself in their shoes and work to understand their perspective.
Keep in mind that the best ideas often come out of the synergy between two or more people.
Reserve judgment on new ideas for a day or two. Come back to them when you have the mindset and energy to focus on how they can work, not why they can't.
Use brainstorming sessions to become comfortable to with evolving ideas and solutions.

data.name: Relationship Building
data.description: Enhance your relational intelligence by learning to build trust and authentic relationships with others.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Make a list of those you would like to have stronger relationships with and outline a plan.
Become an interested student of others, especially those who think differently than you.
Aim to connect on a personal level in your interactions with others; share something about yourself and learn about the other person.
Observe people who are skilled at building relationships; take note of patterns in techniques, habits, communication and body language.
For the next three months, spend two or three times the amount you normally invest in building relationships.

data.name: Releasing Control
data.description: Learn to trust others and go with the group by ceding authority and empowering others.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Trust that others have good intentions unless factual evidence proves otherwise.
Give 10% more authority to others than what comes naturally to you; observe the outcome of giving others more latitude.
Think through the responsibilities you would share with others if you knew for certain they would succeed.
Reflect on what prevents you from releasing control to others; consider the pros and cons of a perfectionistic style.

data.name: Resilience
data.description: Increase mental toughness and strengthen the ability to process, and recover from, difficult situations no matter what the circumstance.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Learn to view failure and setbacks as opportunities for growth and deeper meaning rather than debilitating experiences and indicators of your identity.

Invest in mutually supportive relationships, both in and out of the workplace. Intentionally spend time with people who are both caring and critical thinkers, those who can offer both empathy and objective insight when you go through tough times.
Overcome negativity and feelings of fear by opting for an optimistic mindset. In turn, optimism gives you a broader perspective and a reason to persevere.
Develop a personal sense of purpose that goes beyond attaining achievements or happiness. Learn to ask for help to achieve your own sense of purpose.

data.name: Seeking Feedback
data.description: Discern how and when to solicit feedback that will help improve performance.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Research and study effective ways to ask open-ended questions to solicit feedback.
Be open and ask others what more you can do to succeed in your work; assume each person has meaningful and helpful advice.
Cultivate an attitude of humility and seek to learn and improve.
Utilize any processes your organization has to solicit feedback; this can include performance reviews, 360-style feedback or another approach.
Use the SurePeople Prism Lens to solicit feedback on your personality and leadership style.

data.name: Self-Awareness
data.description: Gain a greater sense of self and the effect that actions, behaviors and personal ethics have on others.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Take stock of your skills and development areas to build your self-awareness.
Identify one or two colleagues who will give honest feedback on areas where you need, or want, to improve.
Solicit feedback on your work from a broader group of people; accept feedback non-defensively and try to implement their advice.
Self-awareness is a skill; do a quick assessment of your impact on other people after every interaction.

data.name: Setting Expectations
data.description: Explore step-by-step processes for gaining results by expressing key needs and intentions.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Identify your expectations and write down five steps to achieve each one.
Communicate your expectations with someone else to gain support and build focus on your goals.
Ask a detail-oriented associate what important considerations you might be missing.
Check in with people after you communicate expectations to make sure they understand what you are asking of them.

data.name: Showing Consideration
data.description: Interpret how and when to adjust to the needs of others through a more attentive, helpful interpersonal style.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Identify and express what you appreciate about a colleague.
Ask others how you can be helpful in a situation, and work actively to help them meet their goals.
Practice sacrificing something for someone else on a daily basis.
Review your SurePeople Prism results to understand the degree to which you are shown as considerate. Learn how to extend consideration beyond what you are already doing.
Ensure that you're helping others express their views and aspirations. Make space for others to be heard.

data.name: Showing Empathy
data.description: Demonstrate compassion and kindness by supporting people and acknowledging their efforts and circumstances.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Ask others how they feel about a situation; genuinely listen to their responses and ask how you can support them.
Recognize that affirming what others feel does not necessarily mean you agree or experience the same.
Strive to do at least one unexpected thing every day that will benefit someone else.
Think about the times in your life when others were there to support you; identify what they did to help you and how you can do the same thing for others.
Determine ways to make space for others to open up, share stories and comparisons in order express empathy.

data.name: Social Awareness
data.description: Develop the ability to recognize and foster the strengths of people and teams. Understand a group's relational and team health and learn to foster it.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Be a student of others by striving to learn one thing about another person that you did not know before the interaction.
Observe others around you and jot down what strengths are apparent in how they go about their work. Help support them by championing their competencies to others.
Always remember that there is a reason behind every person's actions. Think about people compassionately versus condescendingly and strive to react constructively towards their actions.
Learn the individual strengths and weaknesses of others in your setting. Recognize how others benefit one another and where conflict arises.

data.name: Speaking Up
data.description: Learn how to share your thoughts and ideas, including in challenging situations.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Ask yourself, What is the worst thing that could happen if I speak up? How likely is it to happen? And could I handle it if it did?
Decide in advance the best person to speak to on a given topic and how you can get them to hear your point of view.
Decide ahead of time what might be the best context in which to speak up. Prepare yourself for speaking by understanding which situations would be best to take control of and interject.
Make eye contact with one person in the group and begin to express your idea. As you continue, make eye contact with others to slowly pull them in as you control the direction of the conversation.
Use pre-wiring to prepare for a moment when you need to speak up. Speak with others before a meeting about ideas you'd like to share to get their buy-in and support.

data.name: Speaking with Purpose
data.description: Become more declarative and confident when speaking.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Write down what's needed in a succinct way and practice sharing it with someone.
Avoid speaking for an extended period of time, which dilutes your message; share in 30 or 60-second bursts and pause in between key points.
Adopt a positive disposition that says, "You miss 100% of the shots you don't take!"
Watch and emulate confident speakers; seek feedback on your speaking style from them and implement their ideas.
Draw on inspirational moments to communicate messages more purposefully.

data.name: Story Telling
data.description: Infuse presentations with anecdotes and metaphors that reveal something about you and that help you make your point.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Identify 3-5 personal or professional situations that helped you learn and grow.
Practice retelling those stories to a trusted friend or advisor.
Fine-tune the story by adjusting the statement of the problem, the level of detail, or the length of the story.
Make sure your story has a clear point that powerfully makes your case.
Practice telling your story in front of groups.

data.name: Strategic Communication
data.description: Identify ways to become a high-impact communicator through proven interpersonal communication approaches.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Practice sharing your communications in front of a mirror or a trusted friend or colleague before you communicate it to your intended audience.
Use purposeful repetition to focus others on the critical aspects of your idea; you may need to share your idea more than once, or in different ways, for people to fully absorb it.
Make your point in a way that will invite questions and comments.
Explain your idea to someone and ask them to paraphrase it for you; this enables you to understand how well you are communicating and how to make improvements.

Use relevant analogies, anecdotes and data to bring your thinking to life in a way that captures others' attention. Consider how to use language that will help others think expansively about the topic.

data.name: Strategic Thinking
data.description: Gain the capacity to look beyond the details to see the bigger picture and become a global thinker.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Think of the big-picture people in your life and imagine how they would assess the project you are working on.
Begin with the end in mind; state or write down what you want to see accomplished. Try to envision the result a year or two in the future and translate what's needed into your plans.
If you knew you couldn't fail, what would you want to do in your situation? Be confident and optimistic about your ability to make big things happen.

Focus on what you want to achieve over an extended period of time (typically 18-36 months). Doing so enables you to think about large-scale advancements without being intimidated by the need to take dramatic steps in the short-term.
Read about how others have refined their strategies in order to help you elevate your strategic thinking to the next level.

data.name: Taking Risks
data.description: Become comfortable with taking risks in order to maximize results and achieve better outcomes.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Adopt a mindset that you'll miss 100% of the shots you don't take.
Investigate and evaluate the worst thing that could happen if you take the risk. How likely is the worst scenario? Could you address the risk proactively?
Think through the risk-benefit ratio of a decision you are considering; higher risk activities typically generate greater rewards.
Ask colleagues to help you identify areas where you could take more risk; initiate steps, then ask them for additional feedback.

data.name: Task Completion
data.description: Organize, prioritize and segment work to meet objectives and expectations.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Create a to-do list and faithfully stick to it. Write it at the start of each day and review it at the end of the day.
Rank tasks using a traffic light system; a green light as primary importance, yellow is secondary, and red is the lowest level of importance. Allocate your time accordingly.
Prioritize the completion of one item at a time. Start small with typical tasks and note how quickly you can complete them.
Group tasks that are similar and work through them in a given amount of time. Take note of how beneficial it is to think of these tasks collectively as one activity.

Tackle tasks that you're not looking forward to by breaking them up into a two step process. Start by reviewing what needs to be done and organizing the appropriate materials. Then take a break before starting in on the actual work of the task.

data.name: Team Building
data.description: Facilitate better teams by understanding how to employ talent based on skills matching.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Take interest in the capabilities and aptitudes of others to engage differently with co-workers.
Clearly identify what others contribute to the team and encourage their participation with expressed appreciation.
Build diversified teams that complement each other rather than looking for people that just get along.
Use an off-site lunch, non-work activity or sports activity to build an environment conducive to teamwork.
Conduct periodic surveys of team members to get feedback on their views of the environment and team dynamics.

data.name: Teamwork
data.description: Learn how to integrate into a team and work effectively in a group setting.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Make an intentional choice to believe that challenges can be better solved in a team environment.
Identify what you believe are the 2-3 most important things you bring to a team. Write them down.
Identify what you believe are the 2-3 most important things each of your work associates bring to the team. Write them down.
Share examples of situations when teamwork has led to greater results, and reinforce its importance.
Encourage others to buy in to a team approach; articulate the benefits of doing so.

data.name: The Art of Communication
data.description: Investigate the art of providing the right information by using language and phrasing appropriate for your audience.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Strive to master the art of being propositional rather than positional; learn to suggest things in a way that builds interest and commitment.
Make more requests than demands when speaking.
Consider how to use prefacing statements to introduce risky ideas; help people understand the assumptions and risks that underlie your proposals.
Use the mirror method to feature the same vocabulary your audience uses to increase their comprehension of your ideas; mirror your audience's language and approach.
Be mindful of the assumptions you make about your audience and be willing to test those assumptions along the way.

data.name: Time Management
data.description: Achieve goals and meet deadlines with strategies and techniques that maximize productivity and manage workloads.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Once a week, take five minutes to write down what is most important to you, in order of priority.
For several weeks, write down the things that are sapping your time and energy; determine how you can reduce their impact on your success and satisfaction.
Take time to organize a to-do list every morning to understand how planning is a critical aspect to managing your time effectively.
Apply the "80/20" concept to your work efforts by focusing more closely on the 20% of things you do that generate 80% of the value you can deliver.

Use your calendar to plan out projects and activities not just meetings. Using this method allows you to perform a calendar analysis to see where you're spending most your time and then make efficiency decisions.

data.name: Using Intuition
data.description: Learn to rely on your instincts, unconscious reasoning and gut feeling to make rapid judgments when necessary.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Start spending time around intuitive people whose ideas can be contagious.
Believe that there are possibilities even when you cannot see them; keep your mind open to new possibilities.
Allow time to think intuitively, and avoid judging or dismissing your ideas until you fully investigate their feasibility.
Listen carefully to your intuition; examine what it is telling you about a potential situation or decision and why you feel that way.

data.name: Work Life Balance
data.description: Be proactive in guarding your personal time, achievement and success by balancing work with home, activity and rest.

developmentStrategyList.dsDescription: Participate in renewing activities in the following areas: recreational, physical, learning, relational, spiritual, family and character growth.
Consider what can be added to or removed from your life that would make it significantly more rewarding.
Take an active stance on managing the boundaries between your personal and professional lives, and make sure you get enough time to recharge and rest.
Articulate your work-life boundaries to those you work with and ask for their support.

Avoid burning out by taking time to disconnect from work and utilize vacation time whenever you need it. Taking even small vacations allows you to recharge and refresh which increases your ability to be creative, productive, and successful.
